post_text:
Due to a fiber optic line cut, Internet and telephone service at Blue Ridge School and Early College is currently unavailable. As a result, teachers at the school are unable to conduct remote learning activities directly with students. Efforts to repair the fiber optic line are underway now, but there is no estimate for the time when Internet and telephone service will be restored. In case of an emergency, families can contact the district office at 586-2311.

#jcpsnc Jackson County Public Schools, NC

post_text:
BREAKING NEWS...
The USDA Secretary of Agriculture announced today (Monday) that funding is now available for school districts to provide meals free of charge to all children age 18 and under. As a result, there are two important changes to the information we released last week:
1: Meals are no longer limited to students who are enrolled in Jackson County Public Schools, NC.
2: Meals are now free for all students regardless of their participation in the free and reduced-price lunch program.
This is great news for the children of our community. For a list of meal pick-up locations, visit www.jcpsnc.org/meals.
#jcpsnc

Meals will be distributed at 6 schools and 18 community locations. For more info and a list of distribution sites, visit www.jcpsnc.org/meals or call the School Nutrition Department at 586-2311 ext. 1936.

INFORMATIONAL ANNOUNCEMENT
The Jackson County Public Schools, NC Board of Education will hold their regular monthly business meeting on August 25, however they will not discuss any changes to the school reentry plan at that meeting. A special called work session will be held on Tuesday, September 1 to evaluate the progress of the school reentry plan and consider whether to remain in Phase 1 or move to Phase 2. Any changes to the current plan would take effect in week 5. Information about the JCPS school reentry plan can be found at www.jcpsnc.org/reentry.

post_text:
IMPORTANT MESSAGE
Beginning Monday, June 8th, the schedule for school bus meal deliveries will change as we are consolidating several bus routes to make the most efficient use of our resources. Due to the route consolidation, we are unable to provide exact delivery times for next week, however, we are confident that meal deliveries should occur up to 30 minutes before or 30 minutes after the usual delivery time.

If you are not able to wait at the delivery location to receive the meals, you are welcome to leave a plastic, sealable container, and the delivery crew will leave the meals in the container for you to pick up later.

We ask for your patience and understanding as we develop the new delivery schedule. If you have questions or concerns, please do not call your school. Instead, for faster service, please call the school nutrition support line at (828) 575-1403.

NCDPI School Nutrition
April 29 at 1:33 PM ·

Did you know Friday, 5/1, is #SchoolNutritionHeroDay? Help us thank our School Nutrition teams across NC for their essential work and tireless efforts to ensure children receive healthy meals by creating a thank you card or sign. If yellow buses come through your neighborhood delivering meals to students, you can make a sign for your yard, sidewalk or driveway to thank them. If you utilize the drive-thru at a school or community meal site, you can create a sign for your car to display a message of gratitude as you drive by. As you say thank you, maintain social distancing to keep school staff, children and families safe. Take photos of your cards or signs and post to social media tagging #NCSchoolNutritionHeroes, @ncschoolmeals and @ncpublicschools so everyone can see and help share the love for our School Nutrition teams.

Here are a few examples of the wonderful thank you messages we have seen. Thanks to Davidson County Schools, Pitt School Nutrition Services, @PenderSchools and Brunswick County Schools.

JCPS Families:
Many of you have done a wonderful job creating great remote learning environments at home. We want to capture your experience and share it with other families who need a few ideas for improving their own at-home learning. If you are willing to help, please record a short video clip(s) with tips, ideas, and examples about one or more of the following:
- How to create a functional & organized learning space.
- How to keep students focused and limit online time.
- How to plan your student's day and track assignments.
- How to have good communications with teachers.
Please record your video in "landscape" format (horizontally; sideways). Upload your video clip(s) to www.jcpsnc.org/share.
We'll have another list of topics later. We look forward to hearing from you!
Jackson County Public Schools, NC #jcpsnc #jcpsremotelearning

post_text:
JCPS families:
Do you have a great photo or video of a JCPS student being awesome while learning remotely? If so, we want to see it! You can upload files at www.jcpsnc.org/share. We are specifically looking for photos and videos in the following areas that we can use to promote, share, and tell the story of Jackson County Public Schools, NC:
-Anything that shows your success at remote learning.
-Creative learning spaces at home where students do their school work.
-Innovative ideas for organizing & keeping up with assignments (storage, calendars, to-do lists, etc.).
-Books students are reading; areas at home where they like to read.
-Ways students are staying active (inside and outside).
-Using technology.
-Communicating with teachers.
-Students making and enjoying healthy snacks.
-Students helping out around the home.
-Students learning a new life skill that will help them in the future.
If you have a photo or video to share, please upload it at www.jcpsnc.org/share.
Pro Tip: Hold your phone or device sideways (horizontal) when taking pictures or capturing video.
#jcpsnc

IMPORTANT UPDATE (3/23/2020)
On Monday, March 23, an executive order from Governor Roy Cooper announced that North Carolina schools will remain closed for in-person instruction until at least May 15.

Teachers are currently planning for remote learning to begin Monday, March 30. More information about remote learning will be provided later this week.

Dates for field trips, proms, and graduations are on-hold for now, and updates will be provided as soon as possible.

We ask for your patience and understanding as we work through this difficult and rapidly changing time. Jackson County Public Schools, NC cares about every student and will always keep their safety and learning as our top priorities.
#jcpsnc

post_text:
It's "Day 2" of the Jackson County Public Schools, NC school bus meal delivery! We have a couple of requests:

- As bad as we hate it, our delivery folks have been advised to avoid all physical contact with anyone at the bus stops. We love seeing people and getting those hugs, but we all need to keep some distance for a little while.

- For a few days, if you receive a phone call between 10:00 a.m. and 1:00 p.m. from a number you don't recognize, please answer the call. It might be from a bus or van driver trying to find your location.

Again, we appreciate your understanding and patience as we figure out the routes and stops so we can get everyone served. Have a wonderful day!
#jcpsnc

What an incredible day! Jackson County Public Schools, NC school food service workers, bus drivers, staff members, and volunteers prepared and delivered 1,450 lunches (for today) and breakfasts (for tomorrow). We had a few expected hiccups, but every day will get a little better. We were especially touched by some of the kind comments and photos we received. We miss those kids so much, and as it turns out, some of them miss us, too! Be proud of your people Jackson County. They're good folks.
#jcpsnc

post_text:
NEW MEAL DELIVERY PROCESS FOR THURSDAY:
Beginning Thursday, March 19, Jackson County Public Schools, NC school buses will run their regular morning routes on a four-hour delay. The buses will pause at each of their usual morning stops and blow the horn. Individuals who would like to pick up meals for children age 1-18 should go to the bus while it is stopped. Staff members on each bus will provide the meals.

Buses should be at each morning stop within 15 minutes of the expected arrival time. To determine the arrival time, simply add four hours to the time the bus usually arrives on a regular school day.

Students who do not ride a school bus in the morning or at all must complete an online form to request meal delivery. The online form is available at www.jcpsnc.org. No sign-up is necessary for students who regularly ride a school bus in the morning.

If you have questions, please call Ashley Taylor at (828) 575-1403.
#jcpsnc

post_text:
UPDATE ON REMOTE LEARNING FOR STUDENTS DURING THE SCHOOL CLOSURE:
The NC State Board of Education will meet Wednesday to provide expectations and clarification on remote learning. Jackson County Public Schools, NC will follow the guidance and timelines that are established for school districts.

At this time, JCPS teachers will be reaching out to students and families to ensure they have what they need to meet basic needs as well as to discuss and collaborate on ideas for learning at home.

Remote learning at home is intended to be supplemental and does not impact grades. K-8 students are encouraged to work on math activities daily, read for at least 30 minutes, and explore research activities. High school students are encouraged to complete any missing work and continue to read daily.

JCPS teachers and administrators are working on plans for continued instruction if an extended school closure occurs and remote learning becomes the expectation.
#jcpsnc

IMPORTANT ANNOUNCEMENT REGARDING CORONAVIRUS RESPONSE:
Jackson County Public Schools, NC will resume classes on a regular schedule Monday, March 16. However, any student or staff member who traveled by airplane or cruise ship over spring break will be checked by the school nurse prior to reporting to class. Additionally, parents who prefer to keep their children at home may do so, and the absence will be excused.
Other steps being taken:
- Any student appearing ill will be sent home.
- School visitors and assemblies will be limited.
- Sporting events will be analyzed case-by-case and follow NCHSAA guidance.
- Options for online learning are being considered.
- Daily communications are occurring with local emergency management and public health officials.

Additional information will be released as it becomes available.
#jcpsnc

shared_text:
WCU Bardo Arts Center
March 8 at 3:05 PM ·

UPDATE: the public reception scheduled on March 22 for the Youth Art Month exhibition has been cancelled in accordance with the UNC System's decision to halt gatherings of 100 people or more due to Coronavirus (COVID-19). However, this exhibition will still be on display to the public through March 22 at Bardo Arts Center in Gallery 130. The WCU Fine Art Museum exhibitions are also still open to the public.

Every March since 1983, Western Carolina University has hosted Youth Art Month! This annual and national observance demonstrates the value of art education for all children. This exhibition includes approximately 400 artworks chosen from the classrooms of ten Jackson County Public Schools by their teachers.

This exhibition is supported by the Jackson County Arts Council and is coordinated by the WCU School of Art and Design.

DEADLINE FRIDAY, MARCH 6
Snack Master Competition
The Jackson County School Health Advisory Council and the Healthy for Life Action Team are sponsoring the 10th Annual Healthy Snack Master Competition. The competition is open to all individuals or groups (i.e. classes, afterschool programs, clubs, etc.) in Kindergarten through 12th grade enrolled in Jackson County Public Schools, NC.
Students are encouraged to create an original recipe and turn it in to their school’s cafeteria manager by Friday, March 6. The top student and group entries will go on to compete in the Healthy Snack Master Competition on the evening of Thursday, March 26.
For more information, please call Laura Cabe, School Nutrition Director at 586-2311 ext. 1936.

PRESCHOOL SCREENING EVENT
The Jackson County Public Schools, NC Preschool Program, in cooperation with the Local Interagency Council for Young Children will hold an early childhood screening event for children ages 3-5 this Saturday, February 15 from 9:00 a.m. to 1:00 p.m. at the Community Resource Center (the Old Webster School) at 1528 Webster Road.

The free event will include developmental, speech and language (both English and Spanish), vision, and hearing screenings.

Professor Whizpop, Western North Carolina’s favorite magical entertainer will also be there. For more information, contact Petra Giles at Fairview School. Telephone 586-2819, extension 1214.

Parents, we are so thankful and appreciative of the wonderful partnership we have in caring for the children you entrust to us each day. We have no higher priority than keeping them safe. We are concerned that some of you may not have received a call from your child’s school about the early dismissal Friday morning. The superintendent personally contacted each school prior to 8:50 AM, and callouts from the schools began minutes later through our mass calling system. If you do not receive calls from your child’s school, please contact the school so they can verify that your information is accurate.
Jackson County Public Schools, NC #jcpsnc

NC Public Schools
January 24 at 1:55 PM ·

Congratulations to nine North Carolina teachers who have been selected as this year's state regional Teachers of the Year. These accomplished educators will compete for the title of 2020 Burroughs Wellcome Fund North Carolina Teacher of the Year. The winners will be announced April 3 at an awards ceremony in Cary.

The 2020 North Carolina Regional Teachers of the Year are:

West: Dawn Gilchrist, School of Alternatives (Jackson County Public Schools, NC)
Northwest: Maggie Murphy, Piney Creek School (Alleghany County Schools North Carolina)
Southwest: Chad Beam, Burns High School (Cleveland County Schools)
Piedmont Triad: Tonya Smith, Elkin High School (Elkin City Schools)
Sandhills: Maureen Stover, Cumberland International Early College High School, (Cumberland County Schools)
North Central: Carol Forrest, Long Mill Elementary (Franklin County Schools)
Northeast: Jeanette Owens, Ocracoke School (Hyde County Public School System)
Southeast: Daniel Scott, Swansboro High School (Onslow County Schools)
Charter schools: Ashley Bailey, Roxboro Community School, Roxboro

shared_text:
Jackson County Arts Council
January 16 at 3:21 PM ·

WE HAVE A WINNER!!!

Today, we got to present the winner of the inaugural Jackson County Arts Council's tshirt design competition. We were blown away with the entries we received and had a very hard decision. We chose the winning artwork because it displayed many different aspects of what makes Jackson County so unique... dogwood trees, waterfalls and the historic courthouse, which is where our office is located.

AND THE WINNER IS....
Josie Smoker, senior at Jackson Community School (formerly known as School of Alternatives) and an enrolled member of the Eastern Band of Cherokee Indians. What an amazing young woman and artist! We give thanks to her art teacher, Christina Daniels, for encouraging Josie to enter the competition and supporting her throughout the process. Great teachers produce outstanding students and artists. Congratulations Josie and Ms. Daniels!

T-shirts will be available for purchase soon. Please consider purchasing a shirt to support JCAC and so you can own a piece of Josie's artwork! When she's a famous artist one day you will wish you had a shirt...just saying!

She will now compete with the seven other regions in North Carolina for the title of "Burroughs-Wellcome NC Teacher of the Year." shared_text:
Rotary Club of Sylva
December 13, 2019 at 11:05 AM ·

Happy to support our friends at Jackson County Public Schools, NC - the Greatest School System in the World - with the tremendous "Stuff the Bus" project. The annual event is held to collect donations, food, toiletries, and personal items to assist students who are homeless or disadvantaged. At Thursday's meeting we donated $202 from Happy Dollars. Pictured are Ashley Taylor, project coordinator, and Kelly Doppke, Director of Student Support Services, receiving our donation from President Mike. You can help by donating cash or gift cards. Gift cards to local grocery and shoe stores are preferred. They also need lots of food, toiletries, and personal items to stock the seven "Comfort Closets" located in our schools. They need snack items, small individually-packaged microwaveable food, basic toiletries, and personal hygiene items.If you have questions, contact project coordinator Ashley Taylor at (828) 586-2311 ext. 1922 or email ataylor@jcpsmail.org. You can also follow the Student Support Services Facebook page at JCPS Student Support Services.

OPPORTUNITY!
"Stuff the Bus" is underway! The annual event is held to collect donations, food, toiletries, and personal items to assist students who are homeless or disadvantaged. We got off to a great start last weekend at the Dillsboro Luminaire Festival, and even Rudolph and a few elves stopped by for a visit. We still have a long way to go, so the bus will be back in Dillsboro this coming Friday and Saturday night.

You can help by donating cash or gift cards. Gift cards to local grocery and shoe stores are preferred. We also need lots of food, toiletries, and personal items to stock the seven "Comfort Closets" located in our schools. We need snack items, small individually-packaged microwaveable food, basic toiletries, and personal hygiene items.

If you have questions, contact project coordinator Ashley Taylor at (828) 586-2311 ext. 1922 or email ataylor@jcpsmail.org. You can also follow the Student Support Services Facebook page at JCPS Student Support Services.
Jackson County Public Schools, NC #jcpsnc #stuffthebus #stuffthebuschallenge

JCPS Student Support Services
December 6, 2019 at 7:43 AM ·

Our Stuff the Bus event kicks off tonight at the Luminaries festival in Dillsboro! This miniature school bus was designed and built by students at Jackson Community School. The hood of the bus is designed to collect cash, checks, and gift card donations. The body of the bus will be used to collect food items to be sent home with students over winter break.

We encourage you to take a selfie with the bus and post using #stuffthebuschallenge and #jcpsnc

PLEASE NOTE: clothing is not being accepted during this event. Please contact Ashley Taylor for information at ataylor@jcpsmail.org or 828-586-2311 ext.1922
#stuffthebus #jacksoncounty #studentsupport
